"# Appendix D — Introspection at the boundary: foreign values, sidecars, sockets

Not every value in Motoi is native. Values cross boundaries — from foreign function interfaces, from network sockets, from sidecar processes, from disk. This appendix shows how to describe values you did not create, and where introspection stops being able to help.

## D.1 What is a boundary value?

A boundary value is a value that entered the Motoi runtime from outside. Common sources:

- **File reads** — bytes from disk parsed into strings or forms
- **Network reads** — bytes from a socket
- **Foreign function calls** — return values from JavaScript, Python, Rust bindings
- **Sidecar processes** — output from spawned subprocesses
- **User input** — REPL prompts, form fields, voice
- **Cortex reads from previous sessions** — records written by past runs

Every boundary value has less introspection than a native one because the runtime did not create it and does not know its full history.

## D.2 The introspection story for boundary values

For a value that came from outside, `type-of` still works — the runtime knows the shape of what it received. `length`, `keys`, `record-fields` all work on the structural level.

What does not work automatically:

- Provenance beyond \"came from that boundary\"
- Source location (there is no Motoi source)
- Contract (unless the boundary annotated the value)
- Semantic interpretation (the runtime just sees bytes shaped into a value)

For those, you need to introspect the boundary itself, not just the value.

## D.3 Foreign function values

Motoi can call JavaScript, Python, or native functions through a foreign function interface. The return value comes back as a Motoi value, but its origin is the foreign function.

```scheme
(define result (foreign/call \"my-js-function\" 42))
(type-of result)
;; => hash    ;; Motoi shape

(foreign/origin result)
;; => (:kind ffi :language javascript :function \"my-js-function\" :args (42))
```

`foreign/origin` is a boundary introspection verb. It returns metadata about where the value came from, if the runtime tracked it.

Not every foreign value has origin metadata — the runtime tracks it only when the FFI was configured to. For raw FFI calls with no tracking, `foreign/origin` returns nil.

## D.4 Sidecar processes

A sidecar is a subprocess spawned by Motoi that speaks a protocol over stdin/stdout. Motoi's runtime has sidecar helpers for common protocols.

```scheme
(define sidecar (sidecar/start \"my-tool\"))
(sidecar/type sidecar)
;; => (:kind subprocess :cmd \"my-tool\" :pid 12345 :protocol json)

(define result (sidecar/call sidecar (list :op 'compute :input 42)))
(type-of result)
;; => hash    ;; parsed from JSON

(foreign/origin result)
;; => (:kind sidecar :sidecar 12345 :op compute :args (:input 42))
```

The sidecar itself is introspectable — you can see its pid, its command, its protocol. Values returned through the sidecar can carry origin metadata pointing back at the specific call.

## D.5 Socket values

Data arriving through a network socket is the most opaque boundary. The runtime knows only that bytes arrived; it does not know their intended shape.

```scheme
(define sock (socket/connect \"example.com\" 8080))
(socket/info sock)
;; => (:kind socket :remote \"example.com:8080\" :protocol tcp :status open)

(define data (socket/read sock 1024))
(type-of data)
;; => string    ;; raw bytes
```

To make sense of the data you have to parse it. The introspection layer treats it as a string until you parse. After parsing:

```scheme
(define parsed (parse-json data))
(type-of parsed)
;; => hash
(foreign/origin parsed)
;; => (:kind socket :remote \"example.com:8080\" :read-at 1720000000)
```

The origin traces back to the socket. This is useful for debugging — if a value has unexpected shape, `foreign/origin` tells you where it entered the program.

## D.6 File values

Files are the friendliest boundary. Reading a file gives you a string; parsing gives you forms. Both are fully introspectable.

```scheme
(define contents (read-file \"data.txt\"))
(type-of contents)
;; => string
(length contents)
;; => 1024

(foreign/origin contents)
;; => (:kind file :path \"data.txt\" :read-at 1720000000)
```

If you parsed the file:

```scheme
(define forms (parse contents :filename \"data.txt\"))
(length forms)
;; => 12
(form-pos (car forms))
;; => (:filename \"data.txt\" :line 1 :column 1)
```

Now the forms carry file position metadata (Chapter 7). You can trace any form back to its source location.

