## D.17 The trust boundary

Boundary values require judgment. A value that entered from a trusted source (your own file, your own sidecar) can usually be trusted. A value from an untrusted source (a network socket, a user input) should be validated before use.

Introspection helps here:

```scheme
(define user-input (repl-read))
(type-of user-input)
;; => string

(if (contract-satisfied? '(a b c) user-input)
    (do-something-with user-input)
    (raise-error :kind 'invalid-input :context (list :got user-input)))
```

`contract-satisfied?` checks whether a value matches a contract shape. For boundary values, always check before using.

## D.18 The opaque case

Sometimes a boundary value is truly opaque. A binary blob from a network socket. A handle to a foreign resource. A closure returned from FFI. Introspection can only tell you it exists and what type it is.

```scheme
(define handle (native/get-resource))
(type-of handle)
;; => opaque    ;; runtime does not know its shape
(shape-of handle)
;; => (:mechanical (:type opaque) :prose \"This value is a handle to a native resource. It cannot be introspected further.\")
```

Opaque is honest. The runtime does not pretend to know more than it does.

## D.19 A worked example

You are wiring a Motoi cart to a JavaScript library through FFI. The library returns hash objects. You want to make sure your cart handles them correctly.

```scheme
(define result (foreign/call \"js-lib.compute\" input))
(type-of result)
;; => hash
(keys result)
;; => (:status :data :error)

(cond
  ((equal? \"success\" (hash-ref result :status))
   (process (hash-ref result :data)))
  (else
   (handle-error (hash-ref result :error))))
```

Standard boundary handling. Introspect the shape, branch on the fields, extract the data.

## D.20 A closing observation

Introspection is honest about boundaries. It does not pretend to know what it does not know. When a value came from outside, the introspection layer reports what it can (type, shape) and marks the rest as opaque or unknown.

That honesty is what makes the introspection layer trustworthy at boundaries. You cannot be misled by fabricated origin info; if the origin is unknown, the return is nil, not a guess.

