## D.22 A last thought

The boundary is where Motoi meets the world. Introspection stops being able to guarantee the same depth once a value crosses in from outside. What it can still guarantee — shape, mechanical type, origin metadata when tracked — is enough for most practical debugging.

Onward to Appendix E — reader-time introspection.

## D.23 Deep-seed — the introspection contract at the boundary

For every boundary value, the introspection layer promises:

1. `type-of` will return a symbol from the fifteen-entry vocabulary (or `opaque` if unknown)
2. Structural verbs (`length`, `keys`, `record-fields`) work if the value has that shape
3. `foreign/origin` returns metadata if the runtime tracked the boundary crossing
4. No verb will fabricate origin info that the runtime does not have

Everything else is opt-in. If you need richer introspection for a specific FFI or sidecar, you write the tracking yourself.

## D.24 Deep-seed — a boundary-safe workflow

For values from untrusted boundaries:

1. `type-of` — verify the shape you expected
2. Validate against a contract — raise if wrong
3. Sanitize as needed (escape strings, bound numeric ranges)
4. Log origin to Cortex for provenance tracking
5. Use the value

This five-step reflex protects you from bad inputs and preserves the ability to trace bugs back to their source later.

## D.25 Deep-seed — the graceful degradation

If a runtime does not have boundary tracking configured, `foreign/origin` returns nil for every foreign value. The rest of introspection still works. The value's type, shape, and content are all queryable; only the provenance is missing.

This is graceful degradation. You lose one field; you keep everything else.

Onward to Appendix E.

## D.26 A closing example — a socket-safe parser

```scheme
(define (safe-parse-json-from-socket sock)
  (let* ((data (socket/read sock 1024))
         (parsed (guard-parse-json data)))
    (if (error? parsed)
        (list :error parsed :raw data)
        (list :ok parsed :origin (list :socket (socket/info sock))))))
```

Reads from socket, parses safely, returns either the parsed value with origin metadata or an error with the raw bytes for debugging. The origin metadata is what lets you trace back to the socket when something looks off downstream.

## D.27 One more note

Boundary introspection is where the honesty principle from Chapter 16 becomes visible in practice. The runtime does not know what came from where; it tracks what it can and reports the rest as nil. You build tools that fill in the gaps for your specific application.

The primitives are honest. The applications are yours to build.

Onward to Appendix E.

