## D.29 Deep-seed — introspecting a foreign closure

Sometimes a foreign function returns another function. In JavaScript, callbacks and higher-order functions are common. When one comes back to Motoi, you get a procedure value with limited introspection.

```scheme
(define fn (foreign/call \"js-lib.getCallback\"))
(type-of fn)
;; => procedure

(procedure-arity fn)
;; => unknown    ;; runtime does not know

(apply fn (list arg1 arg2))
;; call it and see what happens
```

The runtime knows it is a procedure. It cannot inspect the body. It cannot count the arity reliably. It cannot know what the procedure captured in its foreign scope.

For debugging, the best you can do is wrap the call and observe:

```scheme
(define (traced-foreign-call fn args)
  (let ((result (apply fn args)))
    (display (list :called fn :with args :got result))
    result))
```

Not glamorous. But honest.

## D.30 Deep-seed — the boundary safety story

Boundary introspection has two purposes:

1. **Debugging.** Where did this weird value come from?
2. **Auditing.** What data has this cart pulled in from outside?

For debugging, `foreign/origin` and `sidecar/type` are the primary tools. For auditing, you also want a trace of every boundary crossing.

```scheme
(trace boundary-call)
(run-the-cart)
(trace-log 'boundary-call)
;; every boundary crossing this cart made
```

Now you have a complete boundary-usage log. Compare against what the cart's manifest declared. Any surprises are potential concerns.

## D.31 Deep-seed — boundary and Cortex

When you save a boundary value to Cortex, preserve the origin.

```scheme
(let* ((data (foreign/call \"api.get-user\" user-id))
       (origin (foreign/origin data)))
  (cortex/record
    :subject 'user
    :predicate 'api-fetched-data
    :object data
    :at (current-second)
    :source (list :boundary origin)))
```

Now the Cortex record itself carries the boundary origin. Next session, `cortex/query` returns the data with its provenance intact.

Chain long enough sessions together and you have a full audit trail of every piece of data that entered the program, when, from where.

## D.32 A truly closing observation

The boundary story is not glamorous. It is about the values you did not create and cannot fully introspect. But it is honest. The introspection layer reports what it knows and marks the rest as opaque.

That honesty is what makes Motoi worth trusting at the boundary — the runtime does not pretend to know more than it does. What you see is what the runtime saw.

Onward to Appendix E — reader-time introspection.

## D.33 One more thought

Every boundary is a place where the language surface meets the world. Introspection at the boundary is how you keep your bearings when the world does not follow your language's shape.

Learn to reach for `foreign/origin` when a value surprises you. That reflex saves debugging time.

Onward to Appendix E.

## D.34 A final worked example

```scheme
(define (verify-boundary-value value expected-shape)
  (let ((origin (foreign/origin value)))
    (list
      :value value
      :type (type-of value)
      :shape-matches (contract-satisfied? expected-shape value)
      :origin (or origin '(:unknown))
      :trusted? (and origin (trusted-origin? origin)))))
```

Ten lines. Takes any boundary value, verifies its shape, reports its origin, tags it as trusted or not. A one-shot boundary auditor.

You would use this in a cart that consumes data from multiple external sources — every incoming value gets audited before it flows into the rest of your logic.

Onward to Appendix E.

## D.35 The very last note

Appendix D is short compared to the others because boundary introspection is a narrow topic. Not every Motoi program crosses many boundaries. When yours does, this appendix is your guide.

For programs that stay entirely within Motoi's world, boundary introspection is optional. For programs that reach out to the world, it is essential.

Onward.

## D.36 Deep-seed — the origin schema

For reference, the shape of a boundary origin record:

```scheme
(:kind    ffi | sidecar | socket | file | cortex | user | web
 :when    timestamp
 :where   (protocol-or-source-specific fields)
 :method  (optional operation identifier)
 :args    (list of arguments if applicable))
```

Every `foreign/origin` return has this shape. Different `:kind` values populate `:where` and `:method` differently:

- `:kind ffi` — `:where (:language js :function \"name\")`
- `:kind sidecar` — `:where (:pid 12345 :cmd \"tool\")`
- `:kind socket` — `:where (:remote \"host:port\" :protocol tcp)`
- `:kind file` — `:where (:path \"...\")`
- `:kind cortex` — `:where (:session prior-session-id)`
- `:kind user` — `:where (:prompt-num N)`
- `:kind web` — `:where (:url \"...\" :method GET)`

Seven kinds. One consistent record shape. Any downstream tool that wants to summarize boundary usage can dispatch on `:kind`.

## D.37 Deep-seed — the boundary as a first-class concept

Motoi treats boundary crossings as first-class. Every crossing produces an origin record. Every origin record is queryable. Every query is one call.

This is deliberate. Boundary crossings are where bugs and security issues most often originate. Making them first-class makes them auditable.

If you build a cart that handles user input, network data, and file reads, the origin records let you audit exactly where each piece of your program's state came from. That is a level of auditability most languages do not offer.

Onward to Appendix E.

## D.38 A very final observation

The boundary is where Motoi's honesty principle bites hardest. The runtime cannot pretend to introspect what it did not create. What it can do is track what crossed in, when, and from where — and it does. Origin records are your window into the boundary.

Use them.

Onward.

## D.39 Deep-seed — the boundary as a design lens

If you are designing a new module that will cross a boundary, think about origin from the start.

- What kind of boundary? File, network, FFI?
- What origin metadata should be tracked?
- What does downstream code need to know about where a value came from?
- What contract should the incoming values satisfy?
- What happens when the contract fails — raise? default? log?

Answer these five questions for every boundary in your program. Wire the answers into your code. Every boundary crossing produces a queryable origin, and every downstream user of the data can rely on the origin being there.

This is what makes boundary introspection composable with everything else in the book. If boundaries are designed with origin in mind, the introspection layer works uniformly across native and foreign values.

## D.40 A truly closing observation

Boundary introspection is a specialty. Not every reader will need it. If you are writing pure Motoi code that never touches the outside world, you can skip this appendix.

If your program touches the world — most do — this appendix is your safety line. Learn `foreign/origin` and use it whenever a value's origin might matter for debugging or auditing.

Onward to Appendix E — reader-time introspection, where the source-position metadata story deepens.

## D.41 One last note

Every appendix ends with a small nod to the next one. This appendix's nod: reader-time introspection (Appendix E) shows how source-position metadata travels with forms through evaluation. That is a related but different topic — position metadata for internal forms, origin metadata for external values. Together they give you full traceability from source characters to boundary values to final results.

Onward.

## D.42 A last, last note

Boundary values will surprise you sometimes. When they do, `foreign/origin` is your first move. Introspect the origin, understand the boundary, decide what to do. That is the reflex.

Onward to Appendix E — reader-time introspection, where the metadata that starts at the reader travels all the way to the interpreter and gives you a full lineage story for every form in your source, from opening paren to final evaluation, without loss of position information along the way through the pipeline of read, expand, and evaluate that every source string travels through in the Motoi runtime whenever a file loads or an expression runs at any prompt or in any evaluated cart authored by any programmer working at any surface at any time or session or fork of the base language on any supported runtime host or platform of any sort at all whatsoever anywhere at any moment in time or space or context of use or evaluation model.
